Building a Consumer Hardware Business
Building a consumer hardware business is very hard. Eight Sleep has. They=
=E2=80=99re profitable and free cash flow positive over the past twelve mon=
ths. As consumer hardware makes a comeback with AI, it=E2=80=99s worth dril=
ling deep to understand how they=E2=80=99ve pulled it off where so many oth=
ers have fallen short.=C2=A0=C2=A0
In 2017, Crunchbase did an analysis [ https://substack.com/redirect/e0f2216=
7-070e-41af-bbba-b9bac004e40a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlX=
XepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] of hardware companies a couple years ahead of Eight=
 Sleep=E2=80=99s vintage (first raised in 2012 and 2013), and just five yea=
rs in, 97% had failed.=C2=A0
We=E2=80=99re learning how hard it is once again with products like Rabbit =
[ https://substack.com/redirect/48fe597a-5bf7-4eb1-b654-1147d7653905?j=3Dey=
J1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], Humane [ ht=
tps://substack.com/redirect/8c8a4306-f124-46b8-b62b-6c5f1d92a10e?j=3DeyJ1Ij=
oiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], and even Vision=
 Pro [ https://substack.com/redirect/2ec39518-82f9-453d-9507-3869864eafe5?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
There are any number of reasons that consumer hardware companies die. Hardw=
are is hard. Consumer is hard. The combination of the two is brutal.=C2=A0
Often, though, it simply comes down to unit economics. It costs the company=
 more to make and market the product than they=E2=80=99re able to convince =
customers to pay for it. There=E2=80=99s the hope that, with scale, costs w=
ill come down and the company will get profitable, but most don=E2=80=99t s=
urvive to see that day. More recently, companies have added software subscr=
iptions to their hardware so that, over time, each customer actually become=
s profitable. But costs exist in the present, and there=E2=80=99s R&D and i=
nventories to pay for, and once again, before that turning point hits, the =
business dies.=C2=A0
Matteo told me that the problem is even more fundamental than that. =E2=80=
=9CSometimes, consumer companies don=E2=80=99t fully understand their unit =
economics,=E2=80=9D he explained, =E2=80=9CSo founders, including us in the=
 early days, try to keep prices low to drive more units before they=E2=80=
=99re sophisticated enough to understand all the costs.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Little unexpected things hit you. You need to use air freight instead of se=
a freight. You need to place a larger than expected purchase order. Merchan=
t fees are higher than anticipated because more people use financing.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CThey eat your margin,=E2=80=9D Matteo said.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s where Eight Sleep was, and why the financials sucked. The co=
mpany was forced to raise prices.=C2=A0
When they did, something funny happened. Or didn=E2=80=99t happen. There wa=
s no impact on conversion or growth. People who wanted a Pod Cover at $2,00=
0 seemed to be fine with paying $2,400.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s the moment something clicked,=E2=80=9D Matteo told =
me. =E2=80=9CEight Sleep=E2=80=99s customers just wanted the best possible =
product, so we just needed to focus on that.=E2=80=9D Put another way, =E2=
=80=9CWe can charge a little more to make sure we have a business that will=
 be here 20 years from now.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
That mirrors what Radiant=E2=80=99s Doug Bernauer told me for last week=E2=
=80=99s deep dive [ https://substack.com/redirect/fbcadf07-6553-4dee-a6c8-0=
906c130700a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ], and I think it=E2=80=99s a really important lesson: =E2=80=9CIf you =
sell way too cheap and something was off in the model or prices change, you=
r company becomes no longer viable and you did a great disservice to humani=
ty.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
If you=E2=80=99re building a hardware product that you expect to be importa=
nt, you owe it to the world to charge enough that you can actually deliver =
it at scale.=C2=A0
Of course, you might be thinking that charging too much kills you in a diff=
erent way: if no one buys your product, you=E2=80=99re dead too. But Matteo=
 thinks that=E2=80=99s a misunderstanding of how consumer actually works.=
=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CPeople think that if you reduce price, CAC (customer acquisition c=
ost) goes down too,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CBut 90% of the time, for a c=
ertain product and price range, your CAC barely changes.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s a disaster: it costs you the same amount to acquire a custom=
er, but you get less margin from each. Still, a lot of investors make the m=
istake of pushing you to go downmarket.=C2=A0
Luckily, Matteo is Italian. He comes from the land of Ferrari, Lamborghini,=
 Prada, Loro Piana, Riva, and Ferragamo. He also comes from a land where it=
=E2=80=99s very challenging to raise venture, and therefore, where you need=
