pan>.</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-h=
eight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">There are any number of reasons that cons=
umer hardware companies die. Hardware is hard. Consumer is hard. The combin=
ation of the two is brutal.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); fo=
nt-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Often, though,=
 it simply comes down to </span><strong>unit economics. </strong><span>It c=
osts the company more to make and market the product than they&#8217;re abl=
e to convince customers to pay for it. There&#8217;s the hope that, with sc=
ale, costs will come down and the company will get profitable, but most don=
&#8217;t survive to see that day. More recently, companies have added softw=
are subscriptions to their hardware so that, over time, each customer actua=
lly becomes profitable. But costs exist in the present, and there&#8217;s R=
&amp;D and inventories to pay for, and once again, before that turning poin=
t hits, the business dies.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 5=
5); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Matteo told me=
 that the problem is even more fundamental than that. &#8220;Sometimes, con=
sumer companies don&#8217;t fully understand their unit economics,&#8221; h=
e explained, &#8220;So founders, including us in the early days, try to kee=
p prices low to drive more units before they&#8217;re sophisticated enough =
to understand all the costs.&#8221;&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55,=
 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Little unexp=
ected things hit you. You need to use air freight instead of sea freight. Y=
ou need to place a larger than expected purchase order. Merchant fees are h=
igher than anticipated because more people use financing.&#160;</p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">&#8220;They eat your margin,&#8221; Matteo said.&#160;</p><p styl=
e=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 =
0 20px 0;">That&#8217;s where Eight Sleep was, and why the financials sucke=
d. The company was forced to raise prices.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(=
54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">When =
they did, something funny happened. Or didn&#8217;t happen. There was no im=
pact on conversion or growth. People who wanted a Pod Cover at $2,000 seeme=
d to be fine with paying $2,400.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55=
); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>&#8220;Th=
at&#8217;s the moment something clicked,&#8221; Matteo told me. &#8220;Eigh=
t Sleep&#8217;s customers just wanted the best possible product, so we just=
 needed to focus on that.&#8221; Put another way, </span><strong>&#8220;We =
can charge a little more to make sure we have a business that will be here =
20 years from now.&#8221;&#160;</strong></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, =
55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>That mi=
rrors what Radiant&#8217;s Doug Bernauer told me for last week&#8217;s </sp=
an><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/fbcadf07-6553-4dee-a6c8-0906c13=
0700a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" r=
el style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">deep dive<=
/a><span>, and I think it&#8217;s a really important lesson: </span><strong=
>&#8220;If you sell way too cheap and something was off in the model or pri=
ces change, your company becomes no longer viable and you did a great disse=
rvice to humanity.&#8221;</strong><span>&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color:=
 rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">=
If you&#8217;re building a hardware product that you expect to be important=
, you owe it to the world to charge enough that you can actually deliver it=
 at scale.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; li=
ne-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Of course, you might be thinkin=
g that charging </span><em>too</em><span> much kills you in a different way=
: if no one buys your product, you&#8217;re dead too. But Matteo thinks tha=
t&#8217;s a misunderstanding of how consumer actually works.&#160;</span></=
p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; m=
argin: 0 0 20px 0;">&#8220;People think that if you reduce price, CAC (cust=
omer acquisition cost) goes down too,&#8221; he said. &#8220;But 90% of the=
 time, for a certain product and price range, your CAC barely changes.&#822=
1;&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-heigh=
t: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">That&#8217;s a disaster: it costs you the sam=
e amount to acquire a customer, but you get less margin from each. Still, a=
 lot of investors make the mistake of pushing you to go downmarket.&#160;</=
p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; m=
