; position: relative;"><strong>Eight Sleep by the Numbers</strong></h3><p s=
tyle=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin:=
 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Nearly a decade in, it feels like Eight Sleep has final=
ly completed the first leg of its journey: </span><strong>it&#8217;s built =
a free cash flow positive consumer hardware company.</strong><span>&#160;</=
span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: =
26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">It&#8217;s brought in more money over the past t=
welve months than it&#8217;s spent.</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); =
font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Three years =
ago, Eight Sleep had low </span><strong>gross margins</strong><span> (reven=
ue - costs of goods sold) and lower </span><strong>contribution margins</st=
rong><span> (gross margins - CAC). It made a little bit of money on each Po=
d, but not enough to cover all the fixed costs required to run a data and h=
ardware company. It had to hope that those customers would end up spending =
more within the Eight Sleep ecosystem over time, on Autopilot subscriptions=
 or more Eight Sleep products, so that the numbers might turn around long-t=
erm.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; l=
ine-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Today, </span><strong>Eight Sl=
eep has best-in-class gross margins, its CAC has been trending down for fou=
r years in a row, and it is making hundreds of millions in revenue every ye=
ar</strong><span>. They have </span><strong>double-digit % contribution mar=
gins</strong><span>, meaning that they make money on each customer </span><=
strong>immediately</strong><span>, even before high-margin subscription rev=
enue is taken into account.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, =
55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">&#8220;This i=
s how you become free cash flow positive,&#8221; Matteo told me. Earn more =
money than you spend right upfront; let everything that comes beyond that b=
e gravy.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line=
-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Once subscription revenue is take=
n into account, Eight Sleep has a world-class </span><strong>LTV:CAC</stron=
g><span> ratio, meaning that the gross margin expected to be generated by e=
ach customer is multiples higher than the cost to acquire that customer. Th=
is number has improved as gross margin has, and as churn on Autopilot has c=
ome down.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16=
px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Impressively, they&#8217;=
re putting together those unit economics while continuing to grow quickly. =
The company is </span><strong>on pace to nearly double revenue again this y=
ear</strong><span>, with big growth coming from Autopilot and international=
=2E&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: r=
gb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line=
-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Eight Sleep now controls its own destin=
y. It&#8217;s not going to die, unlike thousands of consumer hardware compa=
nies that have come before it. If it continues doing what it&#8217;s doing,=
 it should print bigger piles of cash each year.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color=
: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"=
><span>While there are competitors in the mattress cooling game, like </spa=
n><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/2717c36d-207b-41cd-800b-ba407a8d=
ce19?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" re=
l style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">Chilipad</a=
><span> (acquired by sleepme) and </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/re=
direct/bce49d5b-a18c-4368-9cfc-8a1d5240d678?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7G=
nA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); t=
ext-decoration: underline;">Bed Jet</a><span>, Eight Sleep has surpassed ea=
ch on the product front. They are &#8220;dumb&#8221; products, they do what=
 the user tells them to, while the Pod is &#8220;smart,&#8221; learning and=
 adjusting on its own in ways that humans couldn&#8217;t on their own (espe=
cially while sleeping). Its lead should compound over time as more data mea=
ns smarter decisions and better sleep, which should mean its margins will b=
e protected.</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px;=
 line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>On Pods alone, the business =
could get much larger. Delian reasoned that </span><strong>everyone who own=
s a Tesla should also own a Pod</strong><span>. With 1.8 million Teslas sol=
d last year, that&#8217;s $7.3 billion in revenue based on the Pod 4 Ultra&=
#8217;s starting point. There&#8217;s a long way to go in terms of brand aw=
areness &#8211; Matteo&#8217;s X following isn&#8217;t quite as large as El=
on&#8217;s, for one thing &#8211; but when I asked Matteo about that comp, =
he said he thinks the market is bigger, if they do their jobs right:</span>=
</p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #0c2427; margin: 20px 0; pa=
dding: 0;"><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height=
: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em><span>Every Tesla owner=
 should have a Pod, but even bigger, every Apple Watch owner should have a =
Pod. Apple moves 50 million Watches per year. What Apple is doing is educat=
ing a large piece of the population. People are already open to paying a pr=
emium price for something connected to their health. At the very least, </s=
pan><strong>every Apple Watch Ultra owner should have a Pod.</strong></em><=
span>&#160;</span></p></blockquote><div class=3D"captioned-image-container-=
